{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FdfgYiggndYvdEmdnGZQgQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n1. **SUM(A1:A10) evaluates correctly**\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about one function's logic — the SUM evaluator taking a range and summing values. This is a single algorithm/parsing concern.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess needed.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n- **Unit** — testing the SUM function evaluator in isolation with mocked cell values.\n\n2. **Cascaded formula evaluation (=B1+1 where B1=A1*2)**\n\n\nThis involves multiple cells feeding results into each other, so the real test is whether the dependency resolution and cascading logic work correctly across module boundaries. I could mock individual cell resolution, but the actual failure mode is at the handoff between resolution steps. I'd call this an integration test since it requires the cell resolver and formula evaluator working together.\n\nFor circular dependency detection, the core logic is a graph cycle detection algorithm that could be tested in isolation, but it needs the full reference resolution system active to work properly. I'll lean toward unit since it's fundamentally testing an algorithm rather than module interactions.\n\nNow looking at the individual function tests: VLOOKUP with exact match and key-not-found errors is just testing the function's lookup logic, IF with nested conditions tests the parser and evaluator for nested expressions, and CONCATENATE with empty cell handling tests how that function handles edge cases. All three are unit tests since they're isolated function implementations.\n\nThen there's cross-sheet references like =Sheet2!A1+1, which requires the sheet management system and formula evaluator to work together — that's integration territory since mocking the sheet lookup would hide real integration failures. Similarly, dependency recalculation in topological order involves the dependency graph, change propagation, and formula re-evaluation all coordinating, so that's also integration-level testing where multiple modules need to interact correctly.\n\nUndo functionality is another integration point — the undo stack, formula storage, and dependency recalculation all need to work in concert. And for save/load operations, the real failure mode is about the custom binary format serialization and deserialization working correctly with actual persistence, which is harder to fake with an in-memory filesystem. the failure mode is in the serialization logic, not OS behavior, so a temp file or in-memory stream works fine. For the cascaded formulas, the key is how cells resolve dependencies recursively—that feels like an Integration test. Circular dependency detection is pure graph logic, so Unit works there. The undo and topological recalculation behaviors both need the full system working together, so those are Integration. For save/load, the custom binary format is what matters, and writing to a temp file then reading back captures that.\n\nNow I'm settling on my final classifications and assigning confidence levels for each behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9941,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9941},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6bc15bbc-5493-40ef-a92a-274308354538","uuid":"fd8af706-7f85-4e0e-a3b5-42474a1fc9a7"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FdfgYiggndYvdEmdnGZQgQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TddsZcRVoiApgxRbJ1FjCs","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"=SUM(A1:A10) evaluates to the correct sum of values in cells A1 through A10","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is entirely within the SUM function's range-resolution and summation algorithm — no module boundary is crossed. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. The cell values can be supplied directly to the evaluator; the bug (wrong range expansion, off-by-one, wrong accumulation) surfaces in one function. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: a real integration failure would require the dependency graph or persistence layer to be involved, but SUM over a literal range is pure arithmetic logic.","test_description":"Construct a minimal spreadsheet model with cells A1–A10 set to known numeric values. Evaluate the formula =SUM(A1:A10) and assert the result equals the exact arithmetic sum. Also test with a mix of integers and floats, and with A-row cells containing zeroes and negatives.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A cell referencing another formula cell (=B1+1, B1=A1*2) produces the correct cascaded result","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is not in either formula's individual evaluation but in the handoff: does the formula evaluator correctly request the already-evaluated value of B1 before adding 1? A unit test that mocks the cell-value resolver would always pass and hide a bug where stale or unevaluated intermediate values are returned. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No — two levels of dependency, but no agentic steps. The bug lives at the module boundary between the cell registry and formula evaluator. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: mocking cell resolution hides the exact failure (stale intermediates, evaluation order).","test_description":"Wire together the cell registry and formula evaluator without mocking. Set A1 to a known value, define B1=A1*2 and C1=B1+1. Evaluate C1 and assert it equals A1*2+1. Then mutate A1 and re-evaluate; assert the result tracks correctly, proving live value propagation rather than cached stale values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The engine detects a circular dependency (A1 references B1, B1 references A1) and returns a circular reference error instead of looping","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Cycle detection is a graph algorithm operating on a dependency graph structure. The failure (infinite loop or missing error) is entirely within that algorithm. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. The test only needs to construct a minimal two-node cycle and verify the engine surfaces the correct error code/exception rather than hanging. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: no module handoff boundary is needed — the cell graph can be constructed directly and fed to the cycle-detection routine.","test_description":"Create a two-cell workbook where A1=B1 and B1=A1. Invoke formula evaluation on either cell and assert that a CircularReferenceError (or equivalent sentinel) is returned promptly, not a stack overflow or hang. Also test a longer cycle (A→B→C→A) and verify the same error is returned for every cell in the cycle.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"VLOOKUP with exact match returns the correct value; returns an error when the key is not found","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: VLOOKUP's lookup-and-return logic is self-contained: it scans a range, compares keys, and returns a column value or error. The failure is in that algorithm, not in any module boundary. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. The lookup table can be provided as an in-process cell range; no external I/O is needed. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: the cross-module interaction is only required if the lookup table is populated via formulas, which this behavior does not claim.","test_description":"Populate a small lookup table (5 rows, 3 columns) in the spreadsheet model. Assert VLOOKUP returns the correct column value for a key present in the first column. Assert it returns a #N/A error (or equivalent) for a key not in the table. Also test a key that matches the last row to catch off-by-one errors.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The IF function correctly handles nested conditions (=IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\"))","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Nested IF evaluation is a parsing/AST-traversal problem. Each branch is chosen by the condition evaluator; the failure is in operator precedence, short-circuit logic, or AST node recursion — all within one module. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: A1 is a direct cell value input, not a formula-produced value; no cross-module dependency handoff is described.","test_description":"Set A1 to three distinct values covering all three branches (e.g., 5, 15, 25). Evaluate =IF(A1>10,IF(A1>20,\"high\",\"medium\"),\"low\") for each and assert outputs are \"low\", \"medium\", and \"high\" respectively. Additionally, test with a boundary value (exactly 10 and 20) to verify strict vs. non-strict comparison semantics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"CONCATENATE joins cell values with the correct separator and handles empty cells by skipping them rather than inserting blank strings","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The empty-cell-skipping behavior is entirely in the CONCATENATE argument-iteration loop. The bug (inserting an empty string vs. skipping) lives inside that function. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: cell values (including empty strings) are a direct input to the function; no formula evaluation chain is described, so no module boundary is crossed.","test_description":"Call CONCATENATE with a mix of non-empty and empty cell values (e.g., [\"Hello\", \"\", \"World\"]). Assert the result is \"HelloWorld\" (skipped empty) rather than \"HelloWorld\" with an embedded blank. Also test with all-empty inputs returning an empty string, and with a separator variant (if supported) to verify separator is not added adjacent to skipped cells.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.87,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"A formula referencing a cell in a different sheet (=Sheet2!A1+1) resolves correctly when the referenced sheet exists","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is at the boundary between the formula parser (which must extract the sheet qualifier) and the workbook's sheet registry (which must locate and return the correct sheet object). A unit test mocking the registry lookup would always pass and hide a bug in qualified-reference dispatch. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: the cross-sheet qualifier parsing must call into a real sheet registry; mocking that call would prevent catching dispatch errors.","test_description":"Create a workbook with two real sheets. Set Sheet2!A1 to a known value. Evaluate =Sheet2!A1+1 in a cell on Sheet1 and assert it returns the expected result. Also evaluate a formula referencing a non-existent sheet and assert a #REF! error is returned rather than a crash.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"When a referenced cell's value changes, all dependent formulas are recalculated in the correct topological order","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives at the boundary between three subsystems: change notification (cell mutation triggers dirty-marking), dependency graph traversal (BFS/topological sort), and formula re-evaluation (cells are re-run in sorted order). No single module owns all three; a unit test of any one part in isolation would miss inter-module ordering bugs. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: a test of only the topological sort algorithm does not catch failures in the change-notification-to-recalc handoff.","test_description":"Construct a diamond-shaped dependency graph: D depends on B and C, both of which depend on A. Set A to an initial value, evaluate all cells, then mutate A. Assert that B and C are recalculated before D, and that D's final value reflects the updated A. Include an assertion that no cell is evaluated more than once per mutation to verify topological ordering rather than redundant re-evaluation.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"Undo after editing a formula restores both the formula text and all previously computed dependent values","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The undo operation must: pop the undo stack, restore the formula text in the cell registry, and trigger recalculation of all dependents through the dependency graph. The failure (dependents show stale post-edit values) only surfaces when all three subsystems are wired together. A unit test of the undo stack alone cannot catch a missing recalculation trigger. REAL-INFRA: No. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: the bug lives specifically at the undo→recalculation handoff, not within either subsystem in isolation.","test_description":"Set up a cell B1=A1*2. Record initial values. Edit B1 to B1=A1*3 and verify dependent cells update. Call undo and assert: (1) B1's formula text reverts to =A1*2, and (2) all cells that depend on B1 show values consistent with the reverted formula, not the edited one.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Saving a workbook to disk and loading it back produces identical cell values and formulas with no data loss or floating-point precision change","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the serializer/deserializer modules interacting with each other via the binary format. The bug (precision loss, formula truncation, wrong type tags) only appears when real bytes are written and re-parsed. REAL-INFRA: Writing to a real temp file is needed to exercise actual binary I/O, but the failure is in format correctness, not in OS-level file behavior (locking, permissions, paths). A BytesIO buffer or temp file covers this at Integration level without needing System-level OS behavior. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE for System: the bug is in the binary format encoding/decoding logic, not in OS filesystem behavior; an in-process stream or temp file reproduces the exact failure.","test_description":"Construct a workbook with cells containing integers, IEEE-754 doubles (including numbers that lose precision in decimal representation), formula strings, and empty cells. Serialize to a temp file using the production serializer. Deserialize using the production deserializer. Assert bit-exact equality for all float values (compare with struct.pack round-trip), exact string equality for all formula texts, and that formula cells re-evaluate to the same results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9941,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9941},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6bc15bbc-5493-40ef-a92a-274308354538","uuid":"254bbbbf-48ce-4cd2-a5b5-e76e8c072842"}
